{
  "card_id": "mitigation_block",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Mitigation Block",
  "aliases": [
    "ob dragged over",
    "OB dragged over",
    "Old Order Block reused",
    "old order block reused",
    "减伤块"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A price structure where a prior order block, after being violated by price, becomes a support/resistance zone. It forms either as a reversal pattern (low-high-higher low-higher high for bullish, or high-low-lower high-lower low for bearish) without sweeping a swing high/low, or as a dragged-over old order block from the opposite side of the market maker curve, used for reaccumulation/redistribution. Often overlaps with Fair Value Gap for higher probability.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a prior order block (up-close for bullish, down-close for bearish) at a price reversal point.",
    "Observe price sweeping a swing high/low and then reversing, indicating the order block was not activated (failed displacement).",
    "For reversal pattern: confirm sequence low→high→higher low→higher high (bullish) or high→low→lower high→lower low (bearish), without sweeping an opposite swing high/low like a breaker.",
    "For dragged-over block: locate old up-close (bullish) or down-close (bearish) order blocks from the opposing curve that have been violated (price closed through them), then extend them horizontally forward to current price action.",
    "Confirm price has displaced and closed through (violated) the order block area before marking it as a mitigation block.",
    "Ensure the mitigation block does not require sweeping a prior high/low (distinguishing from Breaker Block).",
    "Check overlap with Fair Value Gap or other PD array for increased probability.",
    "Validate using SMT divergence: check if a correlated asset has a corresponding breaker or has taken a swing high/low that the mitigation block lacks.",
    "In multi-timeframe analysis, lower timeframe mitigation blocks often align with higher timeframe key levels (FVG or Order Block).",
    "Wait for price to retest the block's open, high, or low before entry; set stop at the opposite end of the block's candle (high for short, low for long)."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Mitigation blocks act as high-probability reversal or confluence zones. When overlapping with FVG and confirmed by SMT, they provide low-risk entries. Traders can drop to lower timeframes (e.g., 15s, 1m) to find precise entries with FVG or OTE, targeting higher timeframe objectives. Price retesting the block without breaking suggests trend continuation; a break may signal a new trend. Failure of a mitigation block often turns it into a liquidity target.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Confusing Mitigation Block with original Order Block, ignoring the prerequisite of failed breakout.",
    "Confusing Mitigation Block with Breaker Block: Mitigation does not require sweeping a prior high/low, Breaker does.",
    "Entering before price actually violates (closes through) the old order block area.",
    "Trading without SMT confirmation, leading to failure swings that become liquidity targets.",
    "Entering immediately on first retest without seeing price reaction or reaccumulation within the block.",
    "Ignoring higher timeframe context and treating all similar sequences as valid mitigation blocks.",
    "Trading directly on higher timeframe instead of dropping to lower timeframe for precise entry.",
    "Not checking overlap with other PD arrays (FVG, Volume Imbalance), reducing confidence.",
    "Setting stops incorrectly; should be at the opposite end of the block's candle.",
    "Holding positions after price breaks an intermediate swing high, violating risk management."
  ],
